  "why": "The paper explicitly demonstrates cross-model transferability: ORFUZZ-generated inputs were applied to multiple other LLMs, a transferable subset (ORFUZZSET) was curated (samples that triggered refusals in >=3 of 5 models), and transferability is analyzed (heatmap and multi-model evaluation). However, the fuzzing design itself is model-specific and driven by per-target feedback (category-aware seed selection, asking the target model for refusal reasons, and OR-JUDGE fine-tuning). The method does not include explicit mechanisms aimed at discovering inputs that are transferable across models (e.g., guiding mutation using feedback from surrogate models or multi-model optimization during generation). Therefore the paper demonstrates transferability empirically but does not incorporate explicit design choices to optimize for transferable attack discovery.",
  "evidence": "Page 1, Abstract: \"ORFUZZ’s outputs form the basis of ORFUZZSET, a new benchmark of 1,786 highly transferable test cases that achieves a superior 57.37% average over-refusal rate across 14 diverse LLMs, significantly outperforming existing datasets.\"; Page 10, Section V.C 'Transferability Analysis and Benchmark Construction (RQ4)': \"This experiment assesses the transferability of over-refusal samples generated by ORFUZZ for one target LLM to other LLMs... Samples generated by targeting Phi-3.5 and Mistral-v0.3 demonstrate high transferability... Conversely, samples generated specifically for Llama-3.1 and Gemma-2 exhibit lower cross-model transferability.\"; Page 10, Section V.C: \"we curated a new benchmark dataset, termed ORFUZZSET, comprising 1,786 queries from ORFUZZ’s output that successfully triggered over-refusal in at least three of the five initial target LLMs.\"; Page 6, Section IV-A 'Category-Aware Seed Selection': \"For each category, we compute the over-refusal rate (ORR) of each model... Building on this observation, we propose a novel, safety category-aware MCTS-Explore algorithm that effectively selects seed samples... by prioritizing categories that exhibit higher over-refusal rates.\"; Page 8, Section IV-C 'Safety-Related Probability Prediction': \"We ask the target model to categorize its refusal reasons into three categories...\" (shows design relies on per-target feedback rather than multi-model/surrogate feedback)."
